You should [switch depth buffering on in your scene][1].

The code in this question is largely obsolete and is also incorrect in parts:

 1. For [JavaFX 3D work](https://wiki.openjdk.java.net/display/OpenJFX/3D+Features), it is recommended to use [Java 8](https://jdk8.java.net/download.html).  
 2. For building a cube, use a [Box](http://download.java.net/jdk8/jfxdocs/javafx/scene/shape/Box.html) shape.
 3. For other geometry types, use a [Sphere][2], [Cylinder][3] or [MeshView][4].  
 4. Use [Point][5] and [Ambient][6] lights to illuminate your Scene.
 5. Apply [Materials][7] to your 3D objects to shade them.
 6. Use [Model importers][8] to import complex mesh models.
 7. [Builders](http://mail.openjdk.java.net/pipermail/openjfx-dev/2013-March/006725.html) are deprecated.
 8. For handling animation it is not recommended to spawn another thread, but to use the [JavaFX animation package][9].
 9. For the particular animation in your question, a [RotateTransition][10] is the appropriate animation.
 10. Your solution is not threadsafe.  You should not modify properties of nodes in the active scene graph (e.g. the transform properties of a displayed node) off of the application thread (use [Platform.runLater][11] instead).
 11. You are not creating a scene with [depth buffering][12] set to true.  The depth buffering flag tells JavaFX that it should apply depth sorting and culling to 3D objects.

Also check that your system supports JavaFX 3D:

    System.out.println(
